description: From Middle English prefect and prefecte, from Old French prefect (Mod. French préfet), from Latin praefectus (“one placed in charge, overseer, director, prefect”), from praeficere (“to place in charge”).

entries.meaning: (historical) An official of Ancient Rome who controlled or superintended a particular command, charge, department, etc.
examples: the prefect of the aqueducts; the prefect of a camp, of a fleet, of the city guard, or of provisions; the pretorian prefect, who was commander of the troops guarding the emperor's person

entries.meaning: The head of a department in France.
The head of a county in Albania or Romania.
The head of a prefecture in Japan.
(Britain) A school pupil in a position of power over other pupils.
